- Then `PropertyInfoRegistry` stores just one property and ignores others.
- So, use `PropertyInfoKey` as a cache key instead of `Integer` to resolve hashCode collision.

Improved building TypeMap with ValueReader

Currently, TypeMap will always be cached into TypeMapStore,
even it's had some properties still not be mapped properly.
And it would cause problem when handing source type that is
dynamic type and need a ValueReader to read its value, like
Json, Map, DB ResultSet or Record.

So I had some improvement for these not handling well stuff.
1. ValueReader with new method getAccessor
So when encounter flat dynamic type, like jooq Record, the
accessors get from ValueReader will not depends on the value,
but depends on the metadata.

2. Only cache when TypeMap is completely mapping
When handling some hierarchical dynamic type, we cannot prevent
that the value to not be null. We must not cache for that
situation, so that we can create a new TypeMap next time and next
time, until we got a completely mapped TypeMap and we will cache it.

3. Re-implement how TypeMap determine un-mapped properties
Current implementation of unmapped properties is only check the
top-layer fields. But it's not true about a completely mapped
TypeMap.

a base TypeMap.
So we introduce TypeMap.include and TypeMap.includeBase so that we can
have TypeMap inheritance.

Make accessor, field, mutator into different cache

Currently, we found that when getter/setter had same
method name, then they will have same hash code when
we cache them. Then we had the risk for getting a
mutator when we try getting an accessor.

So I separate mutator, accessor, and field into three
different cache

Merge pull request #138 from jdbernard/master

Add support for mapping to SortedSets destinations.

Add support for mapping to SortedSets destinations.

Previously the CollectionConverter was only discriminating between Lists and
Sets, instanciating an ArrayList if the destination type was a List and a
HashSet if the destination type was a Set. This failed when the destination
type was a SortedSet (HashSet is not a SortedSet).

Rather than change the HashSet to a TereSet for all Sets, a separate check has
been added for SortedSets so that the more performant HashMap is still used
generally and a TreeSet is used only when we know we need a SortedSet.

Two test cases where added. One is to test that the SortedSet mapping works.
The other is to test that HashSets are still used when a SortedSet is not
requested. This second test may not be necessary if we don't care that much
about the implementation backing the mapped property.
